<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter>
<title>Dual spaces</title>
<introduction>
<epigraph>
<p><em>``Duality is an important general theme that has manifestations in almost every area of mathematic."</em></p>
<p><source>Timothy Gowers</source></p>
</epigraph>
<p>Let <m>V</m> be a normed vector space. Let <m>V^*</m> be all continuous linear maps from <m>V</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}</m>. The space <m>V^*</m> is a key tool in studying <m>V</m>. In this chapter we will study the duals of <m>L^p</m>-spaces; the dual of the space of continuous functions on a closed interval; and the dual of the space of continuous functions on a compact Hausdorff space.</p>
</introduction>
<section>
<title>Linear functionals</title>
<p>As each of <m>V</m> and <m>W</m> have a norm, and thus a metric, we can define what it means for a map from <m>V</m> to <m>W</m> to be continuous. Explicitly, a map <m>f \colon V \rightarrow W</m> is continuous if for all <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> there exists <m>\delta&gt;0</m> such that if <m>v,w\in V</m> satisfy <m>\|v-w\|&lt;\delta</m>, then <m>\|f(v) - f(w)\|&lt;\varepsilon.</m></p>
<p>We will be primarily interested in linear maps between vectors. The following proposition gives another characterization of continuity for linear maps.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-bounded-cont">
<p>Let <m>V</m> and <m>W</m> be two normed vector spaces.
    Let <m>T \colon V \rightarrow W</m> be a linear map.
    Then <m>T</m> is continuous if and only if there exists <m>M\geq 0</m> such that</p>
<md> \|T(v)\|\leq M \|v\|</md>
<p>for all <m>v\in V</m>.</p>
</proposition>
<proof>
<p>First suppose that <m>T</m> is continuous.
    There exists <m>\delta &gt;0</m> such that <m>\|v-w\|&lt;\delta</m> then <m>\|T(v) - T(w)\|&lt;1</m>.
    In particular, since <m>T</m> is linear, if <m>\|v\|&lt;\delta</m> then <m>\|T(v)\|\leq 1</m>.
    Take any non-zero <m>v \in V</m>.
    Fix <m>\delta'</m> with <m>\delta&gt;\delta'&gt;0.</m></p>
<md> \left\|\frac{v}{\delta'^{-1}\|v\|}\right\| =\delta'&lt; \delta.</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md> \left\|T\left(\frac{v}{\delta'^{-1}\|v\|}\right)\right\|\ &lt; 1,</md>
<p>and so</p>
<md> \|T(v)\| &lt; \delta'^{-1}\|v\|.</md>
<p>Conversely, suppose there is an <m>M&gt;0</m> such that <m>\|T(v)\|\leq M\|v\|</m> for all <m>v\in V</m>.
    Take <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>, and let <m>\delta = \varepsilon/M</m>.
    Suppose <m>v,w \in V</m> satisfy <m>\|v-w\|&lt;\delta.</m>
    Then</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\|T(v) - T(w)\| &amp; = \|T(v-w)\| \\
        &amp;\leq M\|v-w\|\\
        &amp;&lt; \varepsilon.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Thus <m>T</m> is continuous.</p>
</proof>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>V</m> be a normed vector space.
    A <em>linear functional</em> is a continuous linear map from <m>V</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
<p>Denote by <m>V^*</m> the collection of all linear functionals on <m>V</m>.<idx><h>linear functional</h></idx>
    The space <m>V^*</m> is called the <em>dual space</em> of <m>V</m>.<idx><h>dual space</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<p>If <m>V</m> is a normed linear space, then its dual <m>V^*</m> is a vector space under the usual operations of scaling and addition for functions:</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
(\varphi + \psi)(v) &amp;= \varphi(v) + \psi(v); \text{ and }
    (\alpha \varphi)(v) = \alpha \varphi(v),
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>for all <m>\varphi,\psi \in V^*</m>, <m>v \in V</m> and <m>\alpha \in \mathbb{R}</m>. Further, the norm on <m>V</m> induces a natural norm on <m>V^*</m>.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>V</m> be a normed vector space.
    For <m>\varphi \in V^*</m> define <m>\|\varphi\|_{\mathrm{op}}</m> by</p>
<md> \|\varphi\|_{\mathrm{op}} = \sup\{|\varphi(v)| \colon \|v\|=1\}.</md>
<p>We call <m>\|\cdot\|_{\mathrm{op}}</m> the <em>operator norm</em> on <m>V^*</m>. <idx><h>operator norm</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<p>It is relatively straightforward to show that the operator norm is indeed a norm on <m>V^*</m>. We leave the details as an exericse, Exercise <xref ref="exer-operator-norm"/></p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-operator-norm">
<p>Let <m>V</m> be a normed vector space and let <m>\|\cdot\|_{\mathrm{op}}</m> be the operator norm on the dual <m>V^*</m>.
    Then <m>\|\cdot\|_{\mathrm{op}}</m> is a  norm on <m>V^*</m>.</p>
<p>Further</p>
<md> \|\varphi\|_{\mathrm{op}} = \inf \{M  \colon |\varphi(v)|\leq M\|v\| \text{ for all }v \in V\},</md>
<p>for all <m>\varphi \in V^*.</m></p>
</proposition>
<p>When <m>V</m> is a normed vector space, <m>V^*</m> with the operator norm will be a Banach space. Note, that <m>V^*</m> is a Banach space even if <m>V</m> itself is not a Banach space. We state this result below for posterity, but we will omit the proof.<fn>The proof itself is not too difficult. It will follow from an <m>\varepsilon/3</m> argument using the completeness of the real line; similar to the proof that a uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.</fn></p>
<theorem>
<p>Let <m>V</m> be a normed vector space and let <m>\|\cdot\|_{\mathrm{op}}</m> be the operator norm on the dual <m>V^*</m>.
    Then <m>\|\cdot\|_{\mathrm{op}}</m> is a  norm on <m>V^*</m>.
    Further <m>V^*</m> is a Banach space with the operator norm.</p>
</theorem>
</section>
<section>
<title>The dual of <m>L^p</m>-spaces</title>
<p>In our study of <m>L^p</m>-spaces so far we have, mostly, looked at arbitrary measure spaces. When studying dual spaces, our strongest results will come when we work with <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces. Our first goal is to describe the linear functionals on <m>L^p(X,\mu)</m> when <m>1\leq p&lt;\infty.</m> Here, Hölder's inequality will play a significant role. When <m>p=\infty</m>, the study of the dual is more involved. We will discuss the dual of <m>L^\infty</m>-spaces at the end of this section.</p>
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space, fix <m>p</m> with <m>1\leq p&lt;\infty</m> and let <m>q</m> be conjugate to <m>p</m>. For <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu)</m>, we define a linear map <m>T_g</m> from <m>L^p(X,\mu)</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}</m> by</p>
<md> T_g(f) = \int_X gf\, d\mu.</md>
<p>When <m>p&gt;1</m>, that <m>gf</m> is integrable follows from Hölders inequality; when <m>p=1</m>, <m>g \in L^{\infty}(X,\mu)</m> and so <m>gf</m> is integrable. The linearity of <m>T_g</m> then follows from the linearity of integration. Further,</p>
<md> |T_g(f)| \leq \|g\|_q\|f\|_p</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in L^p(X,\mu)</m>, and so <m>T_g</m> is continuous by Proposition <xref ref="prop-bounded-cont"/>. Thus the map <m>g \mapsto T_g</m> defines a map from <m>L^q(X,\mu)</m> to <m>(L^p(X,\mu))^*</m>.</p>
<lemma xml:id="lem-holder-for-dual">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space, fix <m>p</m> with <m>1&lt; p&lt;\infty</m> and let <m>q</m> be conjugate to <m>p</m>.
The map</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
T \colon &amp; L^q(X,\mu) \rightarrow (L^p(X,\mu))^* \\
    &amp; g \mapsto T_g
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>is a linear isometric map (i.e. <m>\|T_g\|_{\mathrm{op}} = \|g\|_q</m> for all <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu)</m>).</p>
</lemma>
<proof>
<p>The linearity of the map <m>T</m> follows from the linearity of integration.
    Suppose <m>1&lt;p&lt;\infty</m> and take <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu).</m>
    By Hölder's inequality</p>
<md> |T_g(f)| \leq \|g\|_q\|f\|_p</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in L^p(X,\mu).</m>
    Hence <m>\|T_\mathrm{op}\| \leq \|g\|_q.</m>
    By Corollary <xref ref="cor-holder-cor"/>, there is an <m>f \in L^p(X,\mu)</m> with <m>\|f\|_p=1</m> such that</p>
<md> T_g(f) = \|g\|_q,</md>
<p>and hence <m>\|T_g\|_\mathrm{op}=\|g\|_q.</m></p>
</proof>
<p>When <m>p=1</m> we can prove similar, but we need some restrictions on our measure space.</p>
<lemma xml:id="lem-holder-for-dual-p-1">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure space.
    The map</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
T \colon &amp; L^\infty(X,\mu) \rightarrow (L^1(X,\mu))^* \\
    &amp; g \mapsto T_g
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>is a linear isometric map.</p>
</lemma>
<proof>
<p>We, again, have that <m>T</m> is linear, by the linearity of integration.
    Fix <m>g \in L^{\infty}(X,\mu)</m>.
    It is clear that <m>\|T_g\|_\mathrm{op}\leq \|g\|_\infty.</m>
    Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>.
    Let</p>
<md> A= \{ x\in X \colon |g(x)|&gt; \|g\|_\infty - \varepsilon\}.</md>
<p>By the definition of <m>\|g\|_\infty</m>, <m>A</m> has non-zero measure.
    Since <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, there is a <m>B \subseteq A</m> such that</p>
<md> 0 &lt; \mu(B) &lt; \infty.</md>
<p>Let</p>
<md> f(x) = \frac{1}{\mu(B)} \operatorname{sgn}(g(x))\chi_B(x).</md>
<p>Note</p>
<md> \int_X |f|\,d\mu = \frac{1}{\mu(B)}\int_B 1\,d\mu = 1.</md>
<p>Thus <m>f \in L^1(X,\mu)</m> and <m>\|f\|_1=1</m>.
    Further</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\|T_g\|_\mathrm{op} &amp;\geq |T_g(f)|\\ &amp;= \int_X gf\,d\mu\\
        &amp;= \frac{1}{\mu(B)} \int_B |g|\,d\mu\\
        &amp;\geq \frac{(\|g\|_\infty - \varepsilon)\mu(B)}{\mu(B)}\\
        &amp;= \|g\|_\infty -\varepsilon.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>As this holds for all <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>, we have that <m>\|T_g\|_\mathrm{op} = \|g\|_\infty.</m></p>
</proof>
<p>We will show that, when <m>1\leq p&lt;\infty</m>,<fn>In the <m>p=1</m> case we will work with a <m>\sigma</m>-finite space</fn> that the map <m>T</m> is bijective. I.e., we will show that if <m>\varphi \in (L^p(X,\mu))</m> then there is a <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu)</m> such that <m>\varphi = T_g</m>. We need the following lemma first.</p>
<lemma xml:id="lem-functional-in-Lq">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space, let <m>1\leq p&lt;\infty</m> and let <m>q</m> be conjugate to <m>p</m>.
    Suppose <m>g</m> is a measurable function on <m>X</m> such that <m>\{x \in X \colon g(x) \neq 0\}</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite.
    Let</p>
<md> M =\sup\left\{\left| \int_X gf\,d\mu \right| \colon f \in L^p(X,\mu) \text{ simple, and }\|f\|_p=1\right\}.</md>
<p>If <m>M&lt; \infty</m>, then <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu)</m> and <m>\|g\|_q =M.</m></p>
</lemma>
<proof>
<p>First assume <m>p&gt;1</m>, so that <m>q &lt; \infty</m>.
    Let <m>\{E_n\}_n</m> be an increasing sequence of finite measure sets, such that</p>
<md> \bigcup_{n=1}^\infty E_n = \{x \in X \colon g(x) \neq 0 \}.</md>
<p>By the Simple Approximation Theorem, there is a sequence <m>(\phi_n)_n</m> of simple functions converging pointwise to <m>g</m> with <m>|\phi_n|\leq |g|</m>.
    Let <m>g_n = \phi_n \chi_{E_n}</m>.
    For each <m>n</m>, <m>g_n</m> is a simple function which vanishes outside a set of finite measure.
    Thus, <m>g_n \in L^q(X,\mu)</m>.
    For each <m>n</m>, let <m>f_n</m> be the function</p>
<md> f_n = \|g_n\|_q^{1-q}\operatorname{sgn}(g_n)|g_n|^{q-1}.</md>
<p>As in the proof of Corollary <xref ref="cor-holder-cor"/>, <m>\|f_n\|_p = 1.</m>
    Now, by Fatou's Lemma, we have</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\|g\|_q &amp;\leq \liminf_{n\rightarrow \infty} \|g_n\|_q\\
        &amp;= \liminf_{n\rightarrow \infty} \int_X |g_n f_n| \, d\mu \\
        &amp; \leq \liminf_{n\rightarrow \infty} \int_X |g f_n| \, d\mu \\
        &amp; = \liminf_{n\rightarrow \infty} \int_X g f_n \, d\mu\\
        &amp; \leq M.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Thus <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu)</m> and <m>\|g\|_q \leq M.</m>
    By Hölder's inequality, <m>M \leq \|g\|_q</m>, and so <m>\|g\|_q = M.</m></p>
<p>Suppose now that <m>p=1</m> and <m>q = \infty</m>.
    We proceed in a way similar to the proof of Lemma <xref ref="lem-holder-for-dual-p-1"/>.
    Fix <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> and let</p>
<md> A = \{x \colon |g(x)| \geq M + \varepsilon \}.</md>
<p>If <m>\mu(A)&gt;0</m>, then since <m>\{x \in X \colon g(x) \neq 0 \}</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, there exists measurable <m>B \subseteq A</m> such that</p>
<md> 0 &lt; \mu(B) &lt; \infty.</md>
<p>Let</p>
<md> f = \frac{1}{\mu(B)} \operatorname{sgn}(g) \chi_B.</md>
<p>Then <m>\|f\|_1 = 1</m> and <m>\int_X fg\,d\mu \geq M + \varepsilon.</m>
    However, since <m>f</m> is a simple function</p>
<md> \left|\int_X gf \,d\mu\right| \leq M.</md>
<p>This is a contradiction, hence <m>\mu(A) = 0</m>.
    Therefore <m>g \in L^\infty(X,\mu)</m>.
    That <m>\|g\|_\infty = M</m> is clear.</p>
</proof>
<theorem xml:id="thm-riesz-rep-Lp">
<title>Riesz Representation Theorem for <m>L^p</m>-spaces</title>
<p><idx><h>Riesz Representation Theorem</h><h>for <m>L^p</m>-spaces</h></idx>
    Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space, let <m>1&lt;p&lt;\infty</m> and let <m>q</m> be conjugate to <m>p</m>.
    The map</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
T \colon &amp;L^q(X,\mu) \rightarrow (L^p(X,\mu))^*\\   
     &amp;g \mapsto T_g
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>is an isometric, linear bijection.</p>
<p>If <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, then the map</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
T \colon &amp;L^\infty(X,\mu) \rightarrow (L^1(X,\mu))^*\\   
     &amp;g \mapsto T_g
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>is an isometric, linear bijection.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Let <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> be conjugate with <m>1&lt;p,q&lt;\infty</m>.
    That <m>T</m> is a linear isometric map is shown in Lemma <xref ref="lem-holder-for-dual"/>.
    It remains to show that <m>T</m> is a surjective.
    In the proof we will first assume <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is a finite measure space; then a <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure space; finally we will just assume that <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is a measure space.</p>
<p>Assume <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is a finite measure space, and take <m>\varphi \in (L^p(X,\mu))^*.</m>
    Since <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is finite, <m>\chi_E \in L^p(X,\mu)</m> for all <m>E \in \mathcal{M}.</m>
    Define a map <m>\nu</m> on <m>\mathcal{M}</m> by</p>
<md> \nu(E) = \varphi(\chi_E).</md>
<p>Note that if <m>\chi_E = 0</m> almost everywhere, then <m>\varphi(E) = 0</m>, and so <m>\nu(E) = 0.</m>
    In particular, <m>\nu(\emptyset) = 0.</m>
    Let <m>\{E_k\}_{k\geq 1}</m> be a countable collection of disjoint measurable sets, and let <m>E = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k.</m>
    For each <m>k</m>, let <m>B_n = \bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k.</m>
    The sequence <m>(|\chi_{B_n}-\chi_E|^p)_n</m> converges pointwise to <m>0</m>.
    Thus, by the Lebesgue Dominated Convergence theorem, <m>(\chi_{B_n})_n</m> converges to <m>\chi_{E}</m> with respect to the <m>p</m>-norm.
    Thus, by the continuity of <m>\varphi</m>,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{k=1}^\infty \nu(E_k) &amp;= \lim_{n\rightarrow \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n \nu(E_k)\\
        &amp;= \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty} \varphi(\chi_{B_n})\\
        &amp;= \varphi(E)\\
        &amp;= \nu(E).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>We have shown that <m>\nu</m> is a signed-measure on <m>(X,\mathcal{M}).</m>
    Clearly <m>\nu \ll \mu</m>.
    By the Radon-Nikodym Theorem for signed-measures, Corollary <xref ref="cor-signed-Radon-Nikodym"/>, there is a integrable function <m>g</m> on <m>X</m> such that</p>
<md> \nu(E) = \int_E g \,d\mu = \varphi(\chi_E)</md>
<p>for all <m>E \in \mathcal{M}</m>.
    By the linearity of integration, if <m>f \in L^p(X,\mu)</m> is a simple function, then</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X gf\,d\mu.</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md>
    \sup \left\{\left|\int_X gf \,d\mu \right| \colon f \in L^p(X,\mu) \text{ simple, and }\|f\|_p=1\right\}\leq \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}.</md>
<p>Hence, by Lemma <xref ref="lem-functional-in-Lq"/>, <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu).</m>
    As <m>T_g(f) = \varphi(f)</m> for all simple functions <m>f \in L^p(X,\mu)</m>, it follows from Proposition <xref ref="prop-simple-dense"/>, that <m>\varphi = T_g.</m>
    Thus <m>T</m> is surjective.</p>
<p>Assume now that <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite.
    Let <m>\{E_n\}_n</m> be an increasing sequence of finite measure sets, such that <m>X = \bigcup_{n=1}^\infty E_n.</m>
    We embed <m>L^q(E_n,\mu)</m> in <m>L^q(X,\mu)</m> be setting <m>f(x) = 0</m> for <m>x \in X\backslash E_n</m> for each <m>f \in L^q(E_n,\mu)</m>.
    Note that this embedding preserves the <m>q</m>-norm.
    Since <m>\mu(E_n)&lt;\infty</m>, the above arguments shows that for each <m>n</m> there is a <m>g_n \in L^q(E_n,\mu)</m> such that</p>
<md>\varphi|_{L^q(E_n,\mu)} = T_{g_n}.</md>
<p>Thus, <m>\|g_n\|_q \leq \|\varphi\|_{\mathrm{op}}</m> for all <m>n</m>.</p>
<p>By the uniqueness of the Radon-Nikodym derivative in Corollary <xref ref="cor-signed-Radon-Nikodym"/>, if <m>n\geq m</m> then <m>g_n|_{E_m} = g_m</m> almost everywhere.
    Thus, as elements of <m>L^q(X,\mu)</m> we have <m>g_n|_{E_m} = g_m</m> when <m>n \geq m.</m>
    We can thus define a function <m>g</m> almost everywhere by</p>
<md> g(x) = g_n(x) \text{ if } n \in E_n.</md>
<p>Thus, the sequence <m>(|g_n|^q)_n</m> is an increasing sequence, converging pointwise a.e. to <m>|g|^q</m>.
    Hence, by the Monotone Convergence Theorem,</p>
<md> \lim_{n\rightarrow \infty}\int_X |g|^q\,d\mu = \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty} \int_X |g_n|^q\,d\mu \leq \|\varphi\|^q_{\mathrm{op}}.</md>
<p>Hence, <m>g \in L^q(X,\mu)</m>.</p>
<p>Take any <m>f \in L^p(X,\mu)</m>. The sequence <m>(f\chi_{E_n})_n</m> converges pointwise to <m>f</m>.
    By Hölders inequality, <m>fg_n</m> is integrable for all <m>n</m>, and <m>fg</m> is integrable.
    It follows from the Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem, that</p>
<md> \lim_{n\rightarrow n} \int_X fg_n\,d\mu = \int_X fg \,d\mu.</md>
<p>Also, again by the Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem,</p>
<md> \lim_{n\rightarrow \infty}\|f - f\chi_{E_n}\|_p = \lim_{n\rightarrow \infty}\left( \int_X |f-f\chi_{E_n}|^p \right)^{1/p} = 0.</md>
<p>Hence, by the continuity of <m>\varphi</m>,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\varphi(f) &amp;= \lim_{n\rightarrow \infty} \varphi(f \chi_{E_n}) \\
        &amp;= \lim_{n\rightarrow \infty} \int_X fg_n \,d\mu\\
        &amp;= \int_X fg \,d\mu.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Therefore <m>\varphi = T_g</m>, completing the proof for the <m>\sigma</m>-finite case.</p>
<p>Now let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be an arbitrary measure space. 
    Again, if <m>E \subseteq X</m> is measurable we embed <m>L^q(E,\mu)</m> into <m>L^q(X,\mu)</m> by setting functions to be <m>0</m> on <m>X \backslash E</m>.
    By the above argument, if <m>E \subseteq X</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, then there is a <m>g_E\in L^q(E,\mu)</m> such that</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_{E_n} fg_E\,d\mu</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in L^p(E,\mu).</m>
    Note that, by the uniqueness of <m>g_E</m>, if <m>E</m> and <m>F</m> are <m>\sigma</m>-finite with <m>E \subseteq F</m> then <m>g_F|_E = g_E</m> almost everywhere.
    Thus <m>\|g_F\|_q \geq \|g_E\|_q.</m>
    Let</p>
<md> M = \sup \{ \|g_E\|_q \colon E\subseteq X\ \sigma\text{-finite}\}\leq \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}. </md>
<p>Take a sequence <m>\{E_n\}_n</m> of <m>\sigma</m>-finite sets, such that <m>\|g_{E_n}\|_q\|</m> converges to <m>M</m>, and let <m>F = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k.</m>
    Then <m>F</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, and <m>\|g_F\|_q \geq \|g_{E_n}\|_q</m> for all <m>n</m>.\
    Thus <m>\|g_F\|_q = M.</m>
    Suppose now that <m>A</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, with <m>F \subseteq A</m>.
    Then</p>
<md> \int_X |g_A|^q\,d\mu = \int_X |g_F|^q\,d\mu + \int_X |g|^q_{A\backslash F}\,d\mu \leq M^q = \int_X |g_F|^q.</md>
<p>Thus <m>\|g_{A\backslash F}\|_q = 0,</m> and so  <m>g_A = g_F</m> almost everywhere.
    If <m>f \in L^p(X,\mu)</m>, then by Theorem <xref ref="thm-f-integrable"/>, the set</p>
<md> B = \{x \in X \colon f(x) \neq 0\}</md>
<p>is <m>\sigma</m>-finite.
    Thus, the set <m>A = B \cup F</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, and</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\varphi(f) &amp;= \int_X f g_A \,d\mu \\
        &amp;= \int_X f g_F\,d\mu.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence <m>\varphi = T_g</m>, completing the proof for <m>1&lt;p&lt;\infty.</m></p>
<p>When <m>p=1</m> and <m>q = \infty</m> the proof follows a similar vein of reasoning (when we assume <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite).
    The details are left as an exercise, Exericse <xref ref="exer-riesz-rep-p-1"/>.</p>
</proof>
<remark>
<p>Theorem <xref ref="thm-riesz-rep-Lp"/> shows that in order for the dual of <m>L^1(X,\mu)</m> to be (isometrically isomorphic to) <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m>, it is sufficient that <m>\mu</m> be <m>\sigma</m>-finite.
	But is it necessary that <m>\mu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite?
	The proof relies on two key steps: first we show in Lemma <xref ref="lem-holder-for-dual-p-1"/>, that if <m>\mu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, then the map <m>g \mapsto T_g</m> is a norm preserving map from <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m> to <m>(L^1(X,\mu))^*</m>; then in Theorem <xref ref="thm-riesz-rep-Lp"/> we show that the map is surjective.</p>
<p>You will notice, that the proof of Lemma <xref ref="lem-holder-for-dual-p-1"/> does not fully rely on the fact that <m>\mu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite. 
	Indeed, the property we use is that if <m>\mu(A)&gt;0</m>, then there is a <m>B \subseteq A</m> with <m>0&lt;\mu(B)&lt;\infty</m>.
	Measure spaces with this property are called <em>semi-finite</em><idx><h>measure space</h><h>semi-finite</h></idx>.
	Whilst all <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces are semi-finite, not all semi-finite measure spaces are <m>\sigma</m>-finite.
	E.g., if <m>X</m> is an uncountable set and <m>c</m> is the counting measure on all the subsets of <m>X</m>, then <m>(X,P(X),c)</m> is semi-finite but not <m>\sigma</m>-finite.</p>
<p>The proof of surjectivity in Theorem <xref ref="thm-riesz-rep-Lp"/> also does not tell the whole story.
	In order for the map <m>g \mapsto T_g</m> to be surjective, a necessary and sufficient condition is that the measure space is <em>localizable</em>.
	Other than to say that being localizable is a stronger condition than being semi-finite, but a weaker condition than being <m>\sigma</m>-finite, we will say no more on the topic. 
	We refer the interested reader to the treatise of Fremlin <xref ref="Fremlin"/>.</p>
<p>In lieu of a more in-depth discussion on the dual of <m>L^1(X,\mu)</m> when <m>\mu</m> is not <m>\sigma</m>-finite, we refer the reader to Exercise <xref ref="exer-yes-dual"/> and Exercise <xref ref="exer-not-dual"/>.
	In Exercise <xref ref="exer-yes-dual"/>, an example is given of a measure space which is not <m>\sigma</m>-finite, but the dual of <m>L^1(X,\mu)</m> is <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m>.
	In Exercise <xref ref="exer-not-dual"/>, an example is given where the dual of <m>L^1(X,\mu)</m> is not <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m>.</p>
</remark>
<subsection>
<title>The dual of <m>\ell^\infty</m></title>
<p>Notably absent from our discussions so far is the dual of <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m>. The dual of <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m> can be described, but the description is not as neat as for the dual of <m>L^p(X,\mu)</m> when <m>1&lt;p&lt;\infty</m>. In this subsection we will briefly discuss the dual of <m>\ell^\infty</m>. We leave the general theory of the dual of <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m> to a series of exercises: Exercise <xref ref="exer-norm-on-bfa"/>, Exercise <xref ref="exer-bfa-integral"/>, and Exercise <xref ref="exer-kantor"/>.</p>
<example xml:id="ex-dual-of-linf">
<p>Let <m>c_0</m> be the collection of all sequences of real numbers that converge to <m>0</m>.<idx><h sortby="c0">{<m>c_0</m>}</h></idx>
In Exercise <xref ref="exer-c0"/> we establish that <m>c_0</m> is a separable Banach subspace for <m>\ell^\infty</m>.
For <m>a = (a_n)_n \in \ell^1</m>, we define a linear functional <m>T_a</m> on <m>c_0</m> by</p>
<md> T_a((b_n)_n) = \sum_{n=1}^\infty a_nb_n. </md>
<p>Exercise <xref ref="exer-dual-of-c0"/> shows that the map</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
T \colon &amp; \ell^1 \rightarrow (c_0)^* \\
	&amp; a \mapsto T_a
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>is an isometric bijection.
That is, <m>(c_0)^* \simeq \ell^1</m>.</p>
<p>In Exercise <xref ref="exer-dual-of-linf"/> we show that if <m>\varphi \in (\ell^\infty)^*</m> then there is an <m>a \in \ell^1</m> and a <m>\psi \in (\ell^\infty)^*</m> with <m>\psi(b) = 0</m> for all <m>b \in c_0</m> such that</p>
<md> \varphi = T_a + \psi.</md>
<p>It is reasonable to believe that there are non-zero elements <m>\psi \in (\ell^\infty)^*</m> with <m>\psi|_{c_0} = 0</m>.
After all, <m>\ell^\infty</m> is a not separable by Theorem <xref ref="thm-linf-not-separable"/>, and <m>c_0</m> is a separable by Exercise <xref ref="exer-c0"/>.
That <m>\ell^\infty</m> is larger than <m>c_0</m> suggests that <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m> should be larger than <m>(c_0)^*</m>.
Exhibiting <m>\psi</m> with this property is between difficult and impossible.
However, with the Hahn-Banach theorem, a significant theorem in the field of Functional Analysis, one can show that such <m>\psi</m> exist.
Thus <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m> is not the same as <m>\ell^1</m> under the standard isomorphism <m>T</m>.</p>
</example>
<p>In fact <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m> is much larger than <m>\ell^1</m>. We know that <m>\ell^1</m> is separable and that <m>\ell^\infty</m> is not separable. That <m>\ell^\infty</m> is not separable guarantees that <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m> is also not separable, and so <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m> cannot be the same as <m>\ell^1</m> under any map. There are a few ways to show that <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m> is not separable, but all fall outside the remit of this course. We quickly outline the details of two ways in the following remarks, one using topology and one using functional analysis.<fn>These details are included for your edification and to whet your appetite for further study. Don't stress too much if the details are confusing.</fn></p>
<remark>
<p>Consider the natural numbers <m>\mathbb{N}</m> with the discrete topology, i.e. the topology where every subsets of <m>\mathbb{N}</m> is open.
Using the Stone-\u{C}ech compactification from topology, it can be shown that there is a compact Hausdorff space <m>\beta\mathbb{N}</m> containing a homeomorphic copy of <m>\mathbb{N}</m>, such that every bounded function on <m>\mathbb{N}</m> extends uniquely to a continuous bounded function on <m>\beta\mathbb{N}</m>.
The bounded functions on <m>\mathbb{N}</m> are simply <m>\ell^\infty</m>.
Thus, the Stone-\u{C}ech compactification shows that <m>\ell^\infty \simeq C_b(\beta\mathbb{N})</m>.
For each <m>x \in \beta\mathbb{N}</m> we can define a linear functional <m>\phi_x</m> on <m>C_b(\beta\mathbb{N})</m> by</p>
<md> \phi_x(f) = f(x). </md>
<p>One can show that, if <m>x\neq y</m>, then <m>\|\phi_x - \phi_y\|_\mathrm{op} = 1.</m>
The construction of <m>\beta\mathbb{N}</m> guarantees that <m>\beta\mathbb{N}</m> is uncountable.
Using an argument similar to the proof of Theorem <xref ref="thm-linf-not-separable"/>, we can use the uncountable collection <m>\{\phi_x\}_{x\in\beta\mathbb{N}}</m> to show that <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m> is not separable.</p>
<p>In Example <xref ref="ex-dual-of-ell-inf"/> we give a full description of the dual of <m>\ell^\infty</m> using a class of signed measures on <m>\beta\mathbb{N}</m>.</p>
</remark>
<remark>
<p>With functional analysis tools, we can say more.
One can show that if <m>X</m> is a Banach space which is not separable, then the dual space <m>X^*</m> is also not separable.
Proving that the dual of a non-separable space is non-separable relies on the Hahn-Banach theorem.<idx><h>Hahn-Banach theorem</h></idx></p>
<p>Thus, since <m>\ell^\infty</m> is not separable, we cannot have that <m>\ell^1</m> is isomorphic to <m>(\ell^\infty)^*</m>.
We also know that <m>L^\infty([0,1],m)</m> is not separable by Theorem <xref ref="thm-linf-not-separable"/>, and thus <m>(L^\infty([0,1],m)^*</m> is not separable.
As <m>L^1([0,1],m)</m> is separable, by Theorem <xref ref="thm-Lp-separable"/>, we must have that <m>L^1([0,1],m)\not\simeq (L^\infty([0,1],m))^*.</m></p>
</remark>
</subsection>
</section>
<section>
<title>Locally compact Hausdorff spaces</title>
<p>As all continuous functions on <m>[a,b]</m> are necessarily bounded, <m>C([a,b])= C_b([a,b])</m> and <m>C([a,b])</m> is a Banach space with the <m>\sup</m>-norm, see Example <xref ref="ex-Cb-Banach"/>. In Section <xref ref="sec-RMK"/> we will describe the dual space of <m>C([a,b])</m>. We will do this by provingt the (more general) Riesz-Markov-Kakutani Theorem. We begin with some topological preliminaries.</p>
<p>In this section we will review some topological facts. Most will be presented without proof. Details can be found in <xref ref="Folland"/> or <xref ref="Roy"/> (and umpteen more texts).</p>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a topological space. If <m>x \in X</m>, a set <m>A \subseteq X</m> is a <em>neighborhood of <m>x</m></em><idx><h>neighborhood</h></idx> if <m>x \in A</m>, and there is an open set <m>U \subseteq X</m> such that</p>
<md> x \in U \subseteq A.</md>
<p>Take <m>K \subseteq X</m>. A collection of open sets <m>\{U_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m> is an <em>open cover<idx><h>open cover</h></idx> of <m>K</m></em> if <m>K \subseteq \bigcup_{\alpha \in A}</m>. The set <m>K</m> is <em>compact</em><idx><h>compact</h></idx> if given any open cover <m>\{U_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m> of <m>K</m>, there is a finite subcover. That is, there are <m>U_1,\ldots,U_n \in \{U_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m> such that <m>K \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^n U_k</m>.</p>
<p>The following result gives a useful alternative characterization of compactness.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-compact-finite-intersection">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
	The following are equivalent:</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>X</m> is compact;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if  <m>\{F_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m> is a collection of closed sets satisfying <m>\bigcap_{k=1}^nF_k \neq \emptyset</m> for any <m>F_1,\ldots,F_n \in \{F_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m>, then 
		<md> \bigcap_{\alpha\in A}F_\alpha \neq \emptyset.</md>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</proposition>
<p>Given a collection of topology spaces <m>\{X_\alpha\}_{\alpha\in A}</m> we can form the Cartesian product <m>Y = \prod_{\alpha \in A}X_\alpha</m>. The <em>product topology</em> on <m>Y</m> is the topology generated by the sets <m>\prod_{\alpha \in A}U_\alpha</m> where, for each <m>\alpha \in A</m>, <m>U_\alpha \subseteq X_\alpha</m> is an open set, and <m>U_\alpha = X_\alpha</m> for all but finitely many <m>\alpha</m>.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-tychonoff">
<title>Tychonoff's Theorem</title>
<p><idx><h>Tychonoff's Theorem</h></idx>
	Let  <m>\{X_\alpha\}_{\alpha\in A}</m>  be a collection of topological spaces, let <m>Y = \prod_{\alpha \in A}X_\alpha</m> with the product topology. 
	If <m>X_\alpha</m> is compact for all <m>\alpha \in A</m>, then <m>Y</m> is compact.</p>
</theorem>
<p>Tychonoff's Theorem is a non-trivial result. In fact, it can be shown that Tychonoff's Theorem is equivalent to the axiom of choice.</p>
<p>Recall that <m>X</m> is <em>Hausdorff</em><idx><h>Hausdorff</h></idx> if given <m>x,y\in X</m> with <m>x \neq y</m>, there exist open sets <m>U,V \subseteq X</m> such that</p>
<md> x \in U,\ y \in V,\ \text{ and }U \cap V = \emptyset.</md>
<p>Compact Hausdorff spaces are very nice, but if we restrict to compact topological spaces we lose too many important examples. We instead restrict to locally compact spaces:</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
	The space <m>X</m> is <em>locally compact</em> if every point <m>x\in X</m> has a compact neighborhood.</p>
</definition>
<example>
<p>Every compact space is locally compact.</p>
</example>
<example>
<p>The real line <m>\mathbb{R}</m> is locally compact and Hausdorff. Indeed, for any <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m>, the set <m>[x-1,x+1]</m> is a compact neighborhood of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
	More generally, <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is locally compact and Hausdorff. 
	Indeed, if <m>x \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>, then the neighborhood <m>K = \{y \in \mathbb{R}^n \colon \|x-y\|_2\leq 1\}</m> is compact by the Heine-Borel theorem.</p>
</example>
<example>
<p>Every metric space is Hausdorff.
	However, not every metric space is locally compact. 
	In particular, a Banach space <m>V</m> is locally compact if and only if <m>V</m> is finite dimensional.</p>
</example>
<example>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a topological space with the discrete topology, i.e. every subset of <m>X</m> is open.
	Then <m>X</m> is Hausdorff and locally compact.
	Indeed, if <m>x \in X</m>, then <m>\{x\}</m> is a compact neighborhood of <m>x</m>.
	If <m>X</m> has an infinite cardinality, then <m>X</m> is locally compact, but not compact.</p>
</example>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space. We denote by <m>C(X)</m> the space of all continuous real-valued functions on <m>X</m>. We denote by <m>C_b(X)</m> the space of all bounded continuous real-valued functions on <m>X</m>. The space <m>C_b(X)</m> is a normed-vector space with the <m>\sup</m>-norm<idx><h>norm</h><h><m>\sup</m>-norm</h></idx></p>
<md> \|f\|_\infty = \sup_{x\in X} |f(x)|.</md>
<p>A function <m>f \in C(X)</m> <em>vanishes at infinity</em> if, for all <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>, there is a compact set <m>K</m>, such that <m>|f(x)|&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>x \in X \backslash K</m>. Denote by <m>C_0(X)</m> the space of all continuous functions on <m>X</m> which vanish at infinity.</p>
<p>A function <m>f \in C(X)</m> is <em>compactly supported</em><idx><h>continuous function</h><h>compactly supported</h></idx>, or of <em>compact support</em>, if there is a compact set <m>K \subseteq X</m> such that</p>
<md> \{x \in X \colon h(x) \neq 0\} \subseteq K. </md>
<p>When <m>f</m> is compactly supported, we call the closure of <m>\{x \in X \colon h(x) \neq 0\}</m> in <m>X</m>, the <em>compact support of <m>f</m></em>. We denote by <m>C_c(X)</m> the space of all continuous compactly supported functions on <m>X</m>.</p>
<p>These definitions are consistent with the definitions in Example <xref ref="ex-Cb-Banach"/>, Example <xref ref="ex-C0-Banach"/>, and Example <xref ref="ex-Cc-not-Banach"/>. We have that</p>
<md> C_c(X) \subseteq C_0(X) \subseteq C_c(X).</md>
<p>Both <m>C_b(X)</m> and <m>C_0(X)</m> are Banach spaces with the <m>\sup</m>-norm. In general, <m>C_c(X)</m> is not a Banach space. The smallest Banach subspace of <m>C_b(X)</m> containing <m>C_c(X)</m> is <m>C_0(X)</m>. That is, <m>C_0(X)</m> is the closure of <m>C_c(X)</m>.</p>
<p>When we work with the real line, we can often find continuous functions that take desired values on certain sets. We have, for example, does this with piecewise linear functions many times throughout these notes. When working with a more general topological space, it is not clear that we can always find these nice continuous functions. The following proposition shows that for locally compact Hausdorff spaces, we can, at times, find continuous functions to do what we want.</p>
<proposition>
<title>Urysohn's Lemma</title>
<p><idx><h>Urysohn's Lemma</h></idx>
	Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space. Let <m>K \subseteq X</m> be compact and <m>U \subseteq X</m> be open such that <m>K \subseteq U \subseteq X</m>.
	There exists a continuous, compactly supported function <m>f \colon X \rightarrow [0,1]</m> such that <m>f(x) = 1</m> for all <m>x \in K</m> and <m>f(x) = 0</m> for all <m>x \in X \backslash U</m>.</p>
</proposition>
<p>What we have stated here is actually just a special case of Urysohn's Lemma. When working in a metric space, the next example shows that the proof of Urysohn's Lemma is straightforward.</p>
<example>
<p>Suppose <m>X</m> is a metric space with metric <m>d</m> (not necessarily locally compact), and that <m>K \subseteq U \subseteq X</m> with <m>K</m> closed and <m>U</m> open.
	For any closed set <m>F \subseteq X</m>, let <m>d_F</m> be the function on <m>X</m> defined by
	<m>d_F(x) = \inf\{d(x,y)\colon y \in F\}.</m>
	For each closed <m>F</m>, it can be shown that <m>d_F</m> is a continuous function.
	Now, define a function <m>f</m> on <m>X</m> by</p>
<md> f(x) = \frac{d_{X\backslash U}(x)}{d_{X\backslash U}(x) + d_K(x)}.</md>
<p>Then <m>f</m> is a continuous function from <m>X</m> to <m>[0,1]</m> satisfying <m>f(x) = 1</m> for <m>x \in K</m>, and <m>f(x) = 0</m> for <m>x \in X\backslash U</m>.</p>
</example>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space, let <m>K \subseteq X</m> be a compact subset, and let <m>\{U_1,\ldots,U_n\}</m> be an open cover for <m>K</m>.
	A collection of continuous functions <m>h_1,\ldots,h_n</m> from <m>X</m> to <m>[0,1]</m> are <em>partition of unity for <m>K</m> subordinate to <m>U_1,\ldots,U_n</m></em><idx><h>partition of unity</h></idx> if</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>h_i \in C_c(X)</m> for <m>1\leq i \leq n</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>\sum_{i=1}^n h_i(x) = 1</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>; and</p>
</li>
<li><p>the compact support of <m>h_i</m> is a subset of <m>U_i</m> for <m>1\leq i \leq n</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</definition>
<p>The following result is an application of Urysohn's Lemma.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-decomp-of-unity">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space, <m>K \subseteq X</m> be compact, and <m>\{U_1,\ldots,U_n\}</m> be an open cover of <m>K</m>.
	There is a partition of unity for <m>K</m> subordinate to <m>U_1,\ldots,U_n</m>.</p>
</proposition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space. We denote by <m>\mathcal{B}(X)</m> the Borel sets in <m>X</m>. That is, <m>\mathcal{B}(X)</m> is the smallest <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of subsets of <m>X</m> containing all the open subsets of <m>X</m>. Recall that a measure <m>\mu</m> on the measurable space <m>(X,\mathcal{B}(X))</m> is a Borel measure if <m>\mu(K)&lt;\infty</m> for all compact sets <m>K\subseteq X</m>. We will be primarily interested in a special type of Borel measure.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space and let <m>\mu</m> be a Borel measure on <m>(X,\mathcal{B}(X))</m>.
	Take <m>E \in \mathcal{B}(X)</m>.
	The measure <m>\mu</m> is <em>outer regular</em><idx><h>measure</h><h>outer regular</h></idx> on <m>E</m> if</p>
<md> \mu(E) = \inf\{\mu(U) \colon E \subseteq U,\ U \text{ open}\},</md>
<p>and <em>inner regular</em><idx><h>measure</h><h>inner regular</h></idx> on <m>E</m> if</p>
<md> \mu(E) = \sup\{\mu(K) \colon K \subseteq E,\ K \text{ compact}\}.</md>
<p>The measure <m>\mu</m> is a <em>Radon measure</em><idx><h>Radon measure</h></idx> if <m>\mu</m> is outer regular on all Borel sets, and inner regular on all open sets.</p>
<p>A signed Borel measure <m>\nu</m> on <m>(X,\mathcal{B}(X))</m> is a <em>Radon signed measure</em><idx><h>Radon measure</h><h>Radon signed measure</h></idx> if the measure of total variation <m>|\nu|</m> is a Radon measure.</p>
</definition>
<example>
<p>Let <m>m</m> be the Lebesgue measure on the Borel subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
	By Theorem <xref ref="thm-Lebesgue-regular"/>, <m>m</m> is a Radon measure.</p>
</example>
<example>
<p>Let <m>\mu</m> be a Borel measure on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
	By Lemma <xref ref="lem-regular-borel"/>, <m>\mu</m> is outer regular on all Borel sets.
	By Exercise <xref ref="exer-Borel-on-R-Radon"/>, <m>\mu</m> is inner regular on open subsets <m>U \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>, and hence <m>\mu</m> is a Radon measure.</p>
</example>
<example>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space, let <m>x \in X</m> be any pointy, and let <m>\delta_x</m> be the Dirac measure at <m>x</m> on the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}(X)</m>.
	Then <m>\delta_x</m> is a Radon measure.</p>
</example>
</section>
<section xml:id="sec-RMK">
<title>Linear functionals on <m>C_0(X)</m></title>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space. Our goal is to describe the dual space of <m>C_0(X)</m>. We begin with some examples.</p>
<example xml:id="ex-point-evaluation">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space, and take any <m>x \in X</m>.
	The point-evaluation map</p>
<md> \phi_x(f) = f(x) </md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m> is linear.
	Further, for <m>f\in C_0(X)</m>,</p>
<md> |\phi_x(f)|=|f(x)|\leq \|f\|_\infty.</md>
<p>Thus <m>\varphi</m> is a linear functional on <m>C(X)</m> with <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \leq 1</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>U</m> be any open neighborhood of <m>x</m>. 
	By Urysohn's Lemma, there is a continuous function <m>f \in C_c(X) \subseteq C_0(X)</m> such that <m>\|f\|_\infty =1</m> and <m>f(x) = 1</m>.
	Therefore,</p>
<md> |\phi_x(f)| = f(x) = 1 = \|f\|_\infty,</md>
<p>and hence <m>\|\phi_x\|=1</m>.</p>
</example>
<example xml:id="ex-radon-measure-to-functional">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space with Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}(X)</m>,
	and let <m>\mu</m> be a finite Radon measure on <m>(X,\mathcal{B}(X))</m>.
	By Corollary <xref ref="cor-Cont-are-meas"/>, every continuous real-valued function <m>f</m> on <m>X</m> is a measurable function on <m>(X,\mathcal{B}(X))</m>.
	Since <m>\mu</m> is a finite measure, any bounded measurable function on <m>X</m> is integrable.
	Thus, if <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>, then <m>f</m> is integrable.
	Define a linear map from <m>C_0(X)</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, by</p>
<md> \phi_\mu(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu.</md>
<p>Note that, if <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>, then</p>
<md> |\phi_\mu(f)| = \left|\int_X f\,d\mu\right| \leq \|f\|_\infty \mu(X). </md>
<p>Hence, <m>\phi_\mu</m> is a linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m> and <m>\|\phi_\mu\|_\mathrm{op} \leq \mu(X)</m>.</p>
<p>Since <m>\mu</m> is a Radon measure, there is an increasing sequence <m>\{K_n\}_n</m> of compact subsets of <m>X</m> such that</p>
<md>\mu(X) = \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\mu(K_n).</md>
<p>By Urysohn's Lemma, for each <m>n</m> there is a compactly supported positive function <m>f_n</m> on <m>X</m> such that</p>
<md> f_n(x) = 1 \text{ for all }x\in K_n \text{ and }\|f_n\|_\infty = 1.</md>
<p>For each <m>n</m>,</p>
<md> |\phi_\mu(f_n)| =\int_X f_n\,d\mu \geq \int_{K_n} f_n\,d\mu = \mu(K_n).</md>
<p>Hence, for each <m>n</m>,</p>
<md> \|\phi_\mu\|_\mathrm{op} = \sup\{|\phi_\mu(f)|\colon f\in C_0(X),\ \|f\|_\infty = 1\} \geq \mu(K_n).</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md>\|\phi_\mu\|_\mathrm{op} = \mu(X).</md>
</example>
<remark>
<p>Note that Example <xref ref="ex-point-evaluation"/> is a special case of Example <xref ref="ex-radon-measure-to-functional"/>.
	Indeed, if <m>x\in X</m>, and <m>\delta_x</m> is the Dirac measure at <m>x</m>, then</p>
<md> \int_X f\,d\delta_x = f(x)</md>
<p>by Exercise <xref ref="exer-dirac-integration"/>.</p>
</remark>
<p>Let <m>\nu</m> be a finite Radon signed measure on a locally compact space <m>X</m>. Let <m>\nu= \nu_+ - \nu_-</m> be the Jordan decomposition of <m>\nu</m>. Then both <m>\nu_+</m> and <m>\nu_-</m> are finite Radon measures. If <m>f</m> is a Borel measurable function on <m>X</m> which is integrable with respect to <m>|\nu|</m>, we can define the integral of <m>f</m> with respect to <m>\nu</m> by</p>
<md> \int_X f\,d\nu = \int_X f\,d\nu_+ - \int_X f\,d\nu_-.</md>
<p>We can use this to extend Example <xref ref="ex-radon-measure-to-functional"/>.</p>
<example xml:id="ex-radon-signed-measure-to-functional">
<p>Let <m>\nu</m> be a finite Radon signed measure on a locally compact Hausdorff space <m>X</m>.
	For each <m>f \in C_0(X)</m> define <m>\phi_\nu</m> by</p>
<md> \phi_\nu(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu.</md>
<p>Clearly <m>\phi_\nu</m> is linear, by the linearity of integration.
Note that,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\left| \int_X f \,d\nu\right|  &amp;= \left|\int_X f\,d\nu_+ - \int_X f\,d\nu_-\right| \\
	&amp;\leq \int_X|f|\,d\nu_+ + \int_X|f|\,d\nu_- \\
	&amp;= \int_X|f|\,d|\nu|,
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>where the last equality follows from Exercise <xref ref="ex-integration-sum-measures"/>.
Thus, for <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
|\phi_\nu(f)| \leq |\phi_{|\nu|}(f)| \leq \|f\|_\infty |\nu|(X),
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>where the last inequality comes from Exercise <xref ref="ex-radon-measure-to-functional"/>.
	Hence <m>\phi_\nu \in C_0(X)^*</m>, with <m>\|\phi_\nu\|_\mathrm{op}\leq |\nu|(X).</m></p>
</example>
<p>In Example <xref ref="ex-radon-signed-measure-to-functional"/> we showed <m>\|\phi_\nu\|_\mathrm{op} \leq |\nu|(X)</m> for a signed measure <m>\nu</m>. We have left open the question of the exact value of <m>\|\phi_\nu\|_\mathrm{op}</m>. This is answered in Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK"/>, where it is shown that <m>\|\phi_\nu\|_\mathrm{op} = |\nu|(X)</m>.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space.
	A linear functional <m>\varphi</m> in the dual space of <m>C_0(X)</m> is <em>positive</em> if <m>\varphi(f)\geq 0</m> for all non-negative functions <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>.<idx><h>linear functional</h><h>positive</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<remark>
<p>Note that, if <m>\varphi\in C_0(X)^*</m> is a positive linear functional, then</p>
<md> \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \sup \{\varphi(f) \colon f\geq 0,\ \|f\|_\infty = 1\}.</md>
<p>That is, the norm of <m>\varphi</m> can be calculated using only non-negative functions, see Exercise <xref ref="exer-norm-of-positive"/></p>
</remark>
<example>
<p>The linear functionals described in Example <xref ref="ex-radon-measure-to-functional"/> (and Example <xref ref="ex-point-evaluation"/>) are positive linear functionals.
	The linear functionals in Example <xref ref="ex-radon-signed-measure-to-functional"/> are not necessarily positive.</p>
</example>
<p>Let <m>\nu</m> be a finite Radon signed measure on a locally compact Hausdorff space <m>X</m>. With the notation from Example <xref ref="ex-radon-measure-to-functional"/> and Example <xref ref="ex-radon-signed-measure-to-functional"/>, we have that</p>
<md> \phi_\nu = \phi_{\nu_+} - \phi_{\nu_-},</md>
<p>when <m>\nu = \nu_+ - \nu_-</m> is the Jordan decomposition of <m>\nu</m>. That is, <m>\phi_\nu</m> is the difference of two positive linear functionals. We will show that we can write any linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m> as the difference of two positive linear functionals. We have seen two theorems called the Jordan Decomposition Theorem: first for signed measures (Theorem <xref ref="thm-jordan-decomp-measure"/>), and then for functions of bounded variation on closed bounded intervals of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> (Theorem <xref ref="thm-jordan-decomp-function"/>). In Proposition <xref ref="prop-jordan-decomp-measure-and-function"/> we saw that restricting Theorem <xref ref="thm-jordan-decomp-measure"/> to Borel signed measures on closed bounded intervals recovers Theorem <xref ref="thm-jordan-decomp-function"/>. That is, the Jordan Decomposition of functions of bounded variation is a special case of the Jordan decomposition of signed measures. We will now state a third theorem called the Jordan Decomposition Theorem, this time for linear functionals. Whilst not yet clear, we will eventually see that this too can be viewed as a special case of the Jordan decomposition of signed measures.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-jordan-decomp-functional">
<title>Jordan Decomposition Theorem</title>
<p><idx><h>Jordan Decomposition Theorem</h><h>for linear functionals</h></idx>
	Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space and let <m>\varphi</m> be a linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m>.
	There are positive linear functionals <m>\phi_+,\phi_- \in C_0(X)^*</m> such that</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m>; and</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op}.</m></p>
</li>
</ol>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>We will first define <m>\phi_+</m> on non-negative functions.
	When <m>f \in C_0(X)</m> with <m>f\geq 0</m> let</p>
<md> \phi_+(f) = \sup\{\varphi(g) \colon 0\leq g \leq f\}. </md>
<p>As <m>\varphi(0)=0</m>, it follows that <m>\phi_+(f)\geq 0</m> for all <m>f\geq 0</m> in <m>C_0(X)</m>.
	Also, if <m>0 \leq g \leq f</m>, then</p>
<md> |\varphi(g)| \leq \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \|g\|_\infty \leq  \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \|f\|_\infty,</md>
<p>thus <m>0\leq \phi_+(f)\leq \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \|f\|_\infty</m>.</p>
<p>We want to show that <m>\phi_+</m> is linear on the non-negative functions.
	If <m>0\leq f \in C_0(X)</m> and <m>c \geq 0</m>, then <m>\phi_+(cf)=c\phi_+(f)</m>.
	If <m>0\leq g_1 \leq f_1</m> and <m>0\leq g_2 \leq f_2</m>, then</p>
<md> 0\leq g_1 + g_2 \leq f_1 + f_2.</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md> \phi_+(f_1 + f_2) \geq \phi_+(f_1) + \phi_+(f_2).</md>
<p>Conversely, if <m>0 \leq g \leq f_1 + f_2</m>, let <m>g_1 = \min\{g,f_1\}</m> and <m>g_2 = g-g_1</m>.
	Then  <m>0\leq g_1 \leq f_1</m> and <m>0\leq g_2 \leq f_2</m>, and so</p>
<md> \varphi(g) = \varphi(g_1) + \varphi(g_2) \leq \phi_+ (f_1)+ \phi_+(f_2).</md>
<p>Hence</p>
<md> \phi_+(f_1+f_2)\leq \phi_+(f_1) + \phi_+(f_2).</md>
<p>Therefore <m>\phi_+(f_1 +f_2)= \phi_+(f_1)+ \phi_+(f_2)</m>.</p>
<p>We will now extend <m>\phi_+</m> to all of <m>C_0(X)</m>.
	If <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>, then <m>f = f_+ - f_-</m>, where <m>f_+</m> is the positive part of <m>f</m>, and <m>f_-</m> is the negative part of <m>f</m>.
	Define</p>
<md>\phi_+(f) = \phi_+(f_+)-\phi_+(f_-).</md>
<p>Note that, if <m>f = g-h</m> where <m>g,h\geq 0</m>, then</p>
<md> f_+ + h = g + f_-,</md>
<p>and so, by the linearity of <m>\phi_+</m> on positive functions,</p>
<md> \phi_+(f)= \phi_+(g)-\phi_+(h).</md>
<p>Thus, if <m>f,g\in C_0(X)</m>. 
	Then</p>
<md> f+g = (f_+ + g_+) - (f_- + g_-),</md>
<p>and so <m>\phi_+(f+g) = \phi_+(f) + \phi_+(g)</m>.
	It is straightforward to show that</p>
<md> \phi_+(cf) = c\phi_+(f)</md>
<p>for all scalars <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m> and <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>.
	Thus <m>\phi_+</m> is linear.
	Further, for any <m>f\in C_0(X)</m>,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
|\phi_+(f)| &amp;\leq \max\{|\phi_+(f_+)|,\phi_+(f_-)\}\\
		&amp;\leq \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \max\{\|f_+\|_\infty,\|f_-\|_\infty\}\\
		&amp;= \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}\|f\|_\infty.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Thus <m>\phi_+ \in C_0(X)^*</m> and <m>\|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} \leq \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>\phi_- = \phi_+ - \varphi</m>.
	Then <m>\phi_- \in C_0(X)^*</m>, and if <m>f\geq 0</m> then</p>
<md> \phi_-(f) = \sup\{\varphi(g) \colon 0 \leq g \leq f\}- \varphi(f)\geq 0.</md>
<p>Thus, <m>\phi_-</m> is positive.</p>
<p>It remains to show that <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op}</m>.
	Since, <m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m>, it is immediate that</p>
<md>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \leq \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op}.</md>
<p>Take <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>. Take non-negative <m>f_1,f_2 \in C_0(X)</m> with <m>\|f_1\|_\infty=\|f_2\|_\infty  = 1</m> such that</p>
<md> \|\phi_+\| = \phi_+(f_1)-\varepsilon/2 \text{ and }\|\phi_-\| = \phi_-(f_2)-\varepsilon/2.</md>
<p>Let <m>f = \max\{f_1,f_2\}.</m> Then, <m>\|f\|_\infty =1</m> and</p>
<md> \|\phi_+\| = \phi_+(f)-\varepsilon/2 \text{ and }\|\phi_-\| = \phi_-(f)-\varepsilon/2.</md>
<p>Take any <m>g \in C_0(X)</m> with <m>0\leq g \leq f</m>.
	Then</p>
<md> -f \leq 2g- f \leq f,</md>
<p>and so <m>\|2g-f\|_\infty \leq \|f\|_\infty=1</m>.
	Thus</p>
<md numbered="true" xml:id="eq-norm-est">
\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}  \geq \varphi(2g-f)
		= \varphi(g) + (\varphi(g) - \varphi(f)).
</md>
<p>Taking the supremum over all <m>g</m> with <m>0\leq g \leq f</m> in  <xref ref="eq-norm-est" text="Equation"/> we get</p>
<md> \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \geq \phi_+(f) + \phi_-(f) = \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op} - \varepsilon.</md>
<p>This holds for all <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>, and hence <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \geq \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op}</m>.
	It now follows that <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op}</m>, as desired.</p>
</proof>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space, and let <m>\varphi</m> be a linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m>.
	If <m>\phi_+</m> and <m>\phi_-</m> are positive linear functionals in <m>C_0(X)^*</m> such that <m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m> and <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op}</m>, then we call <m>\phi_+</m> and <m>\phi_-</m> the <em>Jordan decomposition of <m>\varphi</m></em>.<idx><h>Jordan decomposition</h><h>of a linear functional</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<remark>
<p>You may have concerns with the use of the word <em>the</em> in the above definition.
	Uniqueness was never proved in Theorem <xref ref="thm-jordan-decomp-functional"/>.
	Rather than proving uniqueness directly (and justifying the terminology), we will leave this quibble for now.
	The Jordan decomposition of a linear functional is unique; the uniqueness will be addressed in Corollary <xref ref="cor-jordan-unique"/>.</p>
</remark>
<p>The following theorem goes by several names. Some sources call it the Riesz Representation Theorem; some call it Riesz-Markov Theorem; some call it the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani Theorem. We will leave it unnamed, saving the name <em>Riesz-Markov-Kakutani Theorem</em> for the result that usual bears the name, Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK"/>.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-RMK-positive">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space and let <m>\varphi</m> be a positive linear functional on <m>C_c(X)</m>.
	There is a unique finite Radon measure <m>\mu</m> on <m>X</m> such that</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_c(X)</m>.
	Further, <m>\|\varphi\|= \mu(X)</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>For the purposes of this proof, we introduce a piece of notation:
	if <m>U \subseteq X</m> is an open set, and <m>f \in C_c(X)</m> satisfies <m>0\leq f \leq 1</m> and <m>f</m> has compact support inside <m>U</m>, we will write <m>f \prec U</m>.</p>
<p>When <m>U \subseteq X</m> is a non-empty open set, define</p>
<md> \mu(U) = \sup\{\varphi(f) \colon f \prec U\}, </md>
<p>and define <m>\mu(\emptyset) =0</m>.
	For arbitrary <m>E \subseteq X</m>, define</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) = \inf\{\mu(U) \colon E \subseteq U,\ U \text{ open}\}.</md>
<p>Note that, if <m>U</m> and <m>V</m> are open with <m>U \subseteq V</m>, then <m>\mu(U) \subseteq \mu(V)</m>.
	Hence, if <m>U \subseteq X</m> is open, <m>\mu^*(U) = \mu(U)</m>.
	We will show that <m>\mu^*</m> is an outer measure whose measurable sets include the Borel sets.
	We will then show that <m>\mu^*</m> restricts to a finite Radon measure <m>\mu</m> on the Borel sets satisfying</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_c(X)</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>\{U_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be a collection of open sets, and let <m>U</m> be an open set satisfying</p>
<md> U \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty U_k.</md>
<p>Take <m>f \in C_c(X)</m> with <m>f \prec U</m>, and let <m>K \subseteq U</m> be the compact support of <m>U</m>.
	Since <m>K</m> is compact, there is an <m>n</m>, such that</p>
<md> K \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^n U_k.</md>
<p>By Proposition~{prop: decomp of unity} there are functions <m>h_1,\ldots,h_n \in C_c(X)</m>, such that <m>h_k \prec U_k</m> for each <m>1\leq k \leq n</m>, and</p>
<md> \sum_{k=1}^n h_k(x) = 1 </md>
<p>for all <m>x \in K</m>.
	Hence <m>f = \sum_{k=1}^n fh_k</m>, and <m>fh_k \prec U_k</m> for <m>1\leq k \leq n</m>.
	Hence</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\varphi(f) &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^n \varphi(fh_k) \leq \sum_{k=1}^n \mu(U_k)\leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(U_k).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Therefore,</p>
<md> \mu(U) = \sup\{ \varphi(f) \colon f\prec U\} \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(U_k).</md>
<p>It follows that if <m>E \subseteq X</m>, then</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) = \inf\left\{\sum_{k=1}^\infty \colon \{U_k\}_{k=1}^\infty \text{ open},\ E \subset \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty U_k\right\}.</md>
<p>Hence, by Theorem <xref ref="thm-outer-measure"/>, <m>\mu^*</m> is an outer measure.</p>
<p>To show that Borel sets a <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable, it suffices to show that every open <m>U \subseteq X</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-open.
	Fix open <m>U \subseteq X</m>.
	Take an open set <m>E \subseteq U</m>, and <m>\mu(E) &lt; \infty</m>.
	Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>. 
	Take <m>f \prec E \cap U</m>, such that <m>\varphi(f)&gt;\mu(E\cap U)- \varepsilon/2.</m>
	Let <m>K</m> be the compact support of <m>f</m>.
	Then <m>K</m> is closed, and so <m>E \cap K^c</m> is open.
	Take <m>g \prec E \cap K^c</m>, such that <m>\varphi(g)&gt;\mu(E\cap K^c)- \varepsilon/2.</m>
	Then <m>f + g \prec E</m>, and</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu(E) &amp;\geq \varphi(f+g)	= \varphi(f) + \varphi(g)\\
		&amp;&gt; \mu(E \cap U) + \mu(E \cap K^c) - \varepsilon\\
		&amp;\geq \mu(E \cap U) + \mu(E \cap U^c) - \varepsilon.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence <m>\mu(E) \geq \mu(E\cap U) + \mu(E \cap U^c)</m>.
	As <m>\mu^*</m> is subadditive, it follows that <m>\mu(E) = \mu(E \cap U) + \mu(E \cap U^c)</m>.
	Now, suppose <m>E \subseteq X</m> is an arbitrary set with <m>\mu^*(E)&lt;\infty</m>.
	Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>. There is an open set <m>V</m>, with <m>E \subseteq V</m>, such that</p>
<md>\mu(V) &lt; \mu^*(E) + \varepsilon.</md>
<p>Using that <m>V</m> is open,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(E) + \varepsilon &amp;&gt; \mu(V) = \mu(V\cap U) + \mu(V \cap U^c)\\
		&amp;\geq \mu^*(E\cap U) + \mu^*(E \cap U^c).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>As this holds for all <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>, it folloows that <m>\mu^*(E)\geq \mu^*(E\cap U) + \mu^*(E \cap U^c)</m>, and hence 
	<m>\mu^*(E)= \mu^*(E\cap U) + \mu^*(E \cap U^c)</m>.
	We have thus shown that all open subsets of <m>X</m> are <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable.
	Therefore all Borel sets are <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable.</p>
<p>Let <m>\mu</m> be the restriction of <m>\mu^*</m> to the Borel sets.
	We show that <m>\mu</m> is a finite Radon measure.
	That <m>\mu</m> is outer regular follows immediately from the definition of <m>\mu</m>.
	It remains to show that <m>\mu(K)&lt;\infty</m> for all compact <m>K \subseteq X</m>, and that <m>\mu</m> is inner regular on open sets.
	Fix a compact set <m>K \subseteq X</m>, and fix non-negative <m>f \in C_c(X)</m> such that <m>f(x)\geq 1</m> for all <m>x \in K</m> (note that such an <m>f</m> exists by Urysohn's Lemma).
	For <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> let</p>
<md> U_\varepsilon= \{ x \in X \colon f(x) &gt; 1-\varepsilon\}.</md>
<p>Then <m>U_\varepsilon &gt;0</m> and <m>K \subseteq U</m>.
	If <m>g \prec U_\varepsilon</m>, then</p>
<md> \frac{1}{1-\varepsilon}f - g \geq 0. </md>
<p>Since <m>\varphi</m> is a positive linear functional, it follows that</p>
<md>\frac{\varphi(f)}{1-\varepsilon}\geq \varphi(g).</md>
<p>Taking the supremum over all <m>g \prec U_\varepsilon</m>, we have</p>
<md> \mu(K) \leq \mu(U_\varepsilon) \leq \frac{\varphi(f)}{1-\varepsilon}.</md>
<p>As this holds for all <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>, it follows that</p>
<md>
\mu(K) \leq \varphi(f).
</md>
<p>Now take any open set <m>U</m> with <m>K\subseteq U</m>. By Urysohn's Lemma, there is a <m>f \prec U</m> such that <m>f(x) = 1</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>.
	Thus</p>
<md>
\mu(U)\geq \varphi(f)\geq \mu(K).
</md>
<p>Since <m>\mu</m> is outer regular on <m>K</m>, it follows that</p>
<md numbered="true" xml:id="eq-RMK">
\mu(K) = \inf\{\varphi(f) \colon f(x)\geq 1\text{ for }x\in K\}.
</md>
<p>Hence <m>\mu(K)&lt; \infty</m>.
	Take now any open set <m>U \subseteq X</m>.
	Take any <m>\alpha &lt; \mu(U)</m>, and choose <m>f\prec U</m> such that <m>\varphi(f)&gt;\alpha</m>.
	Let <m>K</m> be the compact support of <m>f</m>.
	Note, if <m>g \in C_c(X)</m> and <m>g(x) \geq 1</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>, then <m>g-f \geq 0</m>, and therefore <m>\varphi(g)\geq \varphi(f)&gt;\alpha</m>.
	Thus, by  <xref ref="eq-RMK" text="Equation"/>, <m>\mu(K) &gt; \alpha</m>.
	We have shown that if <m>\alpha &lt;\mu(U)</m>, then there is a compact set <m>K \subseteq U</m>, such that <m>\alpha &lt; \mu(K) \leq U</m>.
	It follows that</p>
<md>\mu(U) = \sup\{\mu(K) \colon K \subseteq U\ \text{ compact}\}.</md>
<p>That is, <m>\mu</m> is inner regular on <m>U</m>.
	Thus <m>U</m> is a Radon measure.
	Finally,</p>
<md> \mu(X) = \sup\{\varphi(f) \colon f\prec X\} = \sup\{\varphi(f)\colon 0\leq f \leq 1\}= \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}&lt;\infty.</md>
<p>Hence <m>\mu</m> is a finite Radon measure, and <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \mu(X)</m>.</p>
<p>We will now show that</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_c(X)</m>.
	Fix <m>f \in C_c(X)</m> with <m>0\leq f \leq 1</m>
	and fix <m>N \in \mathbb{N}</m>.
	For <m>1\leq j \leq N</m>, let</p>
<md> K_j = \left\{x\in X \colon f(x) \geq \frac{j}{N}\right\}.</md>
<p>Let <m>K_0</m> be the compact support of <m>f</m>.
	For <m>1\leq j \leq N</m>, let</p>
<md> f_j(x) = \min\left\{ \max\left\{ f(x)-\frac{j-1}{N},0 \right\},\frac{1}{N}\right\}.</md>
<p>Equivalently,</p>
<md> f_j(x) = \begin{cases}0 &amp; \text{if }f(x) \notin K_{j-1}\\
	f(x) - \frac{j-1}{N}&amp; \text{if }f(x) \in K_{j-1} \backslash K_j\\
	\frac{1}{N} &amp; \text{if }f(x) \in K_j. \end{cases}</md>
<p>Then <m>f_j \in C_c(X)</m> for <m>1\leq j \leq N</m>, and <m>f = \sum_{j=1}^N f_j</m>.</p>
<p>For each <m>1\leq j \leq N</m>,</p>
<md> \frac{\mu(K_j)}{N} \leq \int_X f_j \,d\mu \leq \frac{1}{N}\mu(K_{j-1}).</md>
<p>Note, if <m>K_{j-1}\subseteq U</m> for an open set <m>U</m>, then <m>Nf_j \prec U</m>.
	Thus, <m>\varphi(f_j) \leq \mu(U)/N</m>.
	Hence, since <m>\mu</m> is outer regular and by  <xref ref="eq-RMK" text="Equation"/>,</p>
<md> \frac{\mu(K_j)}{N} \leq \varphi(f_j) \leq \frac{1}{N}\mu(K_{j-1}).</md>
<p>Since <m>f = \sum_{j=1}^N f_j</m>, we have that</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{N} \sum_{j=1}^N \mu(K_j)&amp;\leq \int_X f\,d\mu \leq \frac{1}{N} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\mu(K_j), \text{ and}\\
		\frac{1}{N} \sum_{j=1}^N \mu(K_j)&amp;\leq \varphi(f) \leq \frac{1}{N} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\mu(K_j).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence</p>
<md> \left| \varphi(f) - \int_X f\,d\mu \right| \leq \frac{\mu(K_0)-\mu(K_N)}{N}\leq \frac{\mu(K_0)}{N}&lt;\infty.</md>
<p>Taking the limit as <m>N \rightarrow \infty</m>, we see that</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu.</md>
<p>As every element of <m>C_c(X)</m> is a linear combination of norm one positive functions, we have
	<m> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu</m> for all <m>f \in C_c(X)</m>, as desired.</p>
<p>It remains to show that <m>\mu</m> is unique.
	Suppose <m>\nu</m> is a finite Radon measure on <m>X</m> that also satisfies <m>\varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu</m> for all <m>f \in C_c(X)</m>.
	Take an open set <m>U \subseteq X</m>.
	If <m>f \prec U</m>, then</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X \,d\nu \leq \nu(U).</md>
<p>Also, if <m>K \subseteq U</m> is compact, then by Urysohn's lemma there is an <m>f \prec U</m> such that <m>f(x) = 1</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>.
	Thus,</p>
<md> \nu(K) \leq \int_X f\,d\nu = \varphi(f).</md>
<p>Since <m>\varphi</m> is inner regular on <m>U</m>, it follows that</p>
<md> \nu(U) = \sup\{\varphi(f) \colon f \prec U\}.</md>
<p>Hence <m>\nu = \mu</m> on all open subsets of <m>X</m>.
	As <m>\nu</m> and <m>\mu</m> are outer regular on all Borel sets, it follows that <m>\nu = \mu</m>.</p>
</proof>
<p>We have shown that every positive linear functional on <m>C_c(X)</m> is given by integration with respect to a finite Radon measure; and we have shown that every linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m> can be written as the difference of two positive linear functionals. We will piece these two things together to give a complete description of the dual space <m>C_0(X)</m>.</p>
<p>We first introduce some notation. When <m>X</m> is a locally compact Hausdorff space, we denote by <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m> all finite Radon measure on <m>X</m>.<idx><h>Radon measure</h></idx> In Exercise <xref ref="exer-radon-vec-space"/> it is shown that <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m> is a vector space. We put a norm on <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m> by setting, for <m>\nu \in \mathcal{M}(X)</m>,</p>
<md> \|\nu\|_\mathrm{var} = |\nu|(X), </md>
<p>where <m>|\nu|(X)</m> is the total variation of <m>\nu</m>. That <m>\|\cdot\|_\mathrm{var}</m> defines is also left to Exercise <xref ref="exer-radon-vec-space"/>.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-RMK">
<title>Riesz-Markov-Kakutani Theorem</title>
<p><idx><h>Riesz-Markov-Kakutani Theorem</h></idx>
	Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space and let <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m> be the space of finite Radon measures on <m>X</m>.
	If <m>\varphi \in C_0(X)^*</m>, then there is a <m>\nu \in \mathcal{M}(X)</m> satisfying</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m> and <m>\|\nu\|_\mathrm{var} = \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}.</m></p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Take <m>\varphi \in C_0(X)^*</m>.
	By Theorem <xref ref="thm-jordan-decomp-functional"/>, there are positive linear functionals <m>\phi_+</m> and <m>\phi_-</m> such that <m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m> and <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op}+ \|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op}</m>.
	Both <m>\phi_+</m> and <m>\phi_-</m> restrict to positive linear functionals on <m>C_c(X)</m>.
	Thus, by Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK-positive"/>, there are finite Radon measures <m>\mu_1</m> and <m>\mu_2</m> on <m>X</m> such that, for <m>f \in C_c(X)</m>,</p>
<md> \phi_+(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu_1 \text{ and }\phi_-(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu_2.</md>
<p>Further, <m>\|\phi_+\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\mu_1\|_\mathrm{var}</m> and <m>\|\phi_-\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\mu_2\|_\mathrm{var}</m>.
	As <m>C_c(X)</m> is dense in <m>C_0(X)</m>, we have</p>
<md> \phi_+(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu_1 \text{ and }\phi_-(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu_2</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>\mu = \mu_1 - \mu_2</m>.
	Then <m>\mu \in \mathcal{M}(X)</m>.
	Let <m>\mu = \mu_+ - \mu_-</m> be the Jordan decomposition of <m>\mu</m>.
	Then, <m>\mu_+ + \mu_2 = \mu_- + \mu_1</m>, and so, by Exercise <xref ref="ex-integration-sum-measures"/>,</p>
<md> \int_X f \,d\mu_+ + \int_X f \,d\mu_2 = \int_X f \,d\mu_- + \int_X f \,d\mu_1, </md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>.
	Rearranging the above equality, we get</p>
<md> \int_X f\,d\mu = \int_X f\,d\mu_1 - \int_X f\,d\mu_2 = \varphi(f),</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>.
	By Example <xref ref="ex-radon-signed-measure-to-functional"/>,</p>
<md> \mu_1(X) + \mu_2(X) = \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} \leq |\mu|(X).</md>
<p>Since <m>\mu = \mu_1 - \mu_2</m>, by Proposition <xref ref="prop-total-variation"/> we also have <m>|\mu|(X) \leq \mu_1(X)+ \mu_2(X)</m>, and so <m>|\mu|(X) = \mu_1(X)+ \mu_2(X)</m>.
	Therefore <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = |\mu|(X)</m>.</p>
<p>We will now prove uniqueness.
	Suppose <m>\nu \in \mathcal{M}(X)</m> also satisfies
	<m>\varphi(x) = \int_X f\,d\nu</m>
	for all <m>f\in C_0(X)</m>.
	Let <m>\nu = \nu_+ - \nu_-</m> be the Jordan decomposition of <m>\nu</m>.
	Then, for <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>, two applications of Exercise <xref ref="ex-integration-sum-measures"/> give</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\int_X f\,d(\nu_+ + \mu_-) &amp;= \int_X f\,d\nu_+ + \int_X f\,d\mu_-\\ &amp;=\int_X f\,d\nu_- + \int_X f\,d\mu_+\\
	&amp;=\int_X f\,d(\nu_- + \mu_+).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>By the uniqueness in Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK-positive"/>, <m>\nu_+ + \mu_- = \nu_- + \mu_+</m>, and hence <m>\nu = \mu</m>.</p>
</proof>
<p>The following corollary follows immediately from Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK"/>.</p>
<corollary xml:id="cor-RMK-Banach">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space, and let <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m> be the finite Radon signed measures on <m>X</m>.
	Let <m>\Phi</m> be the map</p>
<md> \Phi \colon \mathcal{M}(X) \rightarrow C_0(X)^*,</md>
<p>defined by</p>
<md> \Phi(\nu)(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>.
	Then <m>\Phi</m> is an isometric isomorphism.</p>
</corollary>
<p>We can now prove that the Jordan decomposition of a linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m> is unique, using the uniqueness of the Jordan decomposition for signed measures.</p>
<corollary xml:id="cor-jordan-unique">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space, and let <m>\varphi</m> be a linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m>.
	If <m>\phi_1,\phi_2</m> are positive linear functionals on <m>C_0(X)</m> such that <m>\varphi = \phi_1 - \phi_2</m> and <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\phi_1\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_2\|_\mathrm{op}</m>,
	then <m>\phi_1 = \phi_+</m> and <m>\phi_2 = \phi_-</m> where <m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m> is the Jordan decomposition of <m>\varphi</m>.</p>
</corollary>
<proof>
<p>Let <m>\phi_1,\phi_2</m> be positive linear functionals on <m>C_0(X)</m> such that <m>\varphi = \phi_1 - \phi_2</m> and <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\phi_1\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_2\|_\mathrm{op}</m>.
	By Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK"/>, there is a finite Radon signed measure <m>\mu</m>, and finite Radon measures <m>\mu_1</m> and <m>\mu_2</m> such that <m>|\mu|(X) = \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}</m>, <m>\mu_1(X) = \|\phi_1\|_\mathrm{op}</m>, and <m>\mu_2(X) = \|\phi_2\|_\mathrm{op}</m>; and for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m></p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu,\ \phi_1(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu_1,\ \text{ and }\phi_2(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu_2.</md>
<p>Thus, for all <m>f \in C_0(X)</m>,</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu = \int_X f\,d\mu_1 - \int_X f\,d\mu_2 = \int_X f\,d(\mu_1-\mu_2).</md>
<p>Hence, by the uniqueness of <m>\mu</m> from Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK"/>,   <m>\mu = \mu_1 - \mu_2</m>.
	We also have that</p>
<md> |\mu|(X) = \|\phi_1\|_\mathrm{op} + \|\phi_2\|_\mathrm{op} = \mu_1(X) + \mu_2(X).</md>
<p>Therefore, by Proposition <xref ref="prop-total-variation"/>, <m>\mu_1 - \mu_2</m> is the Jordan decomposition of <m>\mu</m>.
	That is <m>\mu_1 = \mu_+</m> and <m>\mu_2 = \mu_-</m>.
	As the Jordan decomposition of the signed measure <m>\mu</m> is unique, by Theorem <xref ref="thm-jordan-decomp-measure"/>, it follows that <m>\phi_1 = \phi_+</m> and <m>\phi_2 = \phi_-</m> where <m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m> is the Jordan decomposition of <m>\varphi</m>.</p>
</proof>
<example>
<p>The set of natural numbers <m>\mathbb{N}</m> with the discrete topology is a locally compact Hausdorff space.
	If <m>c_0</m> is the collection of all sequences which converge to <m>0</m>, then <m>C_0(\mathbb{N}) = c_0</m>.
	By Exercise <xref ref="exer-dual-of-c0"/>, the dual of <m>c_0</m> is <m>\ell^1</m>; and by Corollary <xref ref="cor-RMK-Banach"/> the dual of <m>c_0 = C_0(\mathbb{N})</m> is <m>\mathcal{M}(\mathbb{N})</m>, the space of all finite Radon signed measures on <m>\mathbb{N}</m>.
	Thus <m>\ell^1</m> is isometrically isomorphic <m>\mathcal{M}(\mathbb{N})</m>.</p>
<p>Explicitly, the maps between <m>\ell^1</m> and <m>\mathcal{M}(\mathbb{N})</m> are given as follows:
	for <m>a = (a_n)_n \in \ell^1</m>, the function <m>\nu</m> on subsets of <m>\mathbb{N}</m> defined by</p>
<md> \nu_a(E) = \sum_{n \in E}a_n </md>
<p>defines a finite Radon signed measure on <m>\mathbb{N}</m>.
	For <m>\nu \in \mathcal{M}(\mathbb{N})</m>, we can define a sequence <m>a_\nu = (\nu\{n\})_n</m>.
	Then <m>a_\nu \in \ell^1</m>.
	These two operations are clearly inverses of eachother.</p>
</example>
<example xml:id="ex-dual-of-ell-inf">
<p>Again, consider the set of natural numbers <m>\mathbb{N}</m> with the discrete topology.
	There is a compact Hausdorff space <m>\beta\mathbb{N}</m> containing <m>\mathbb{N}</m> as a dense subset such that</p>
<md> C_b(\mathbb{N}) = C(\beta\mathbb{N}). </md>
<p>The space <m>\beta \mathbb{N}</m> is called the Stone-\u{C}ech compactification of <m>\mathbb{N}</m>.
	Note that <m>\ell^\infty = C_b(\mathbb{N})</m>.
	Thus, by Corollary <xref ref="cor-RMK-Banach"/>,</p>
<md> (\ell^\infty)^* \simeq \mathcal{M}(\beta \mathbb{N}).</md>
<p>That is, the dual of <m>\ell^\infty</m> is (isometrically isomorphic to) the Radon signed measures on the Stone-\u{C}ech compactification of <m>\mathbb{N}</m>.</p>
</example>
<remark xml:id="rem-jordan-comparison">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space.
	Take <m>\varphi \in C_0(X)^*</m>, and let <m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m> be the Jordan decomposition of <m>\varphi</m>.
	Let <m>\mu</m> be the finite Radon signed measure such that</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\mu,</md>
<p>from Theorem <xref ref="thm-RMK"/>.
	Let <m>\mu = \mu_+ - \mu_-</m> be the Jordan decomposition of <m>\mu</m>.
	In Corollary <xref ref="cor-jordan-unique"/> it is shown that <m>\mu_+</m> and <m>\mu_-</m> are the unique measures such that</p>
<md> \phi_+(f) = \int_X f \,d\mu_+\text{ and }\phi_-(f) = \int_X f \,d\mu_-.</md>
<p>In other words, the Jordan decomposition for linear functionals on <m>C_0(X)</m> gives the Jordan decomposition for finite Radon signed measures on <m>X</m> (via the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani Theorem). 
	In this way, the Jordan decomposition for linear functionals can be seen as a special case of the Jordan decomposition for signed measures.</p>
</remark>
<remark>
<p>Let <m>[a,b]\subseteq\mathbb{R}</m> be a closed bounded interval on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, and let <m>g</m> be a right-continuous function of bounded variation on <m>[a,b]</m>.
	By Theorem <xref ref="thm-signed-meas-1-1-bv"/> there is a unique Borel signed measure <m>\nu</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> such that <m>g(x) = \nu([a,x])</m>.
	Let <m>\varphi</m> be the linear functional on <m>C([a,b])^*</m>	defined by <m>\varphi(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu</m>.</p>
<p>Now let <m>g = g_+ - g_-</m>, <m>\nu = \nu_+ - \nu_-</m>, and <m>\varphi = \phi_+ - \phi_-</m> be the Jordan decompositions of <m>g</m>, <m>\nu</m>, and <m>\varphi</m> respectively.
	Then, by Proposition <xref ref="prop-jordan-decomp-measure-and-function"/>,</p>
<md> g_+(x) = \nu_+([a,x]) \text{ and }g_-(x) = \nu_-([a,x]);</md>
<p>and, as discussed in Remark <xref ref="rem-jordan-comparison"/>,</p>
<md> \phi_+(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu_+ \text{ and }\phi_-(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu_-.</md>
<p>Thus, the Jordan decomposition for linear functionals on <m>C([a,b])</m> recovers the Jordan decomposition for right-continuous functions of bounded variation on <m>[a,b]</m>.</p>
</remark>
<subsection>
<title>Riesz's result and Riemann-Stieltjes integration</title>
<p>Riesz gave a description of the dual of <m>C([a,b])</m>, for a closed bounded interval <m>[a,b]\subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>. Riesz described the linear functionals on <m>[a,b]</m> not in terms of integration with respect to Borel measures on <m>[a,b]</m>, but in terms of Reimann-Stieltjes integrals.<idx><h>Riemann-Stieltjes integral</h></idx></p>
<p>Let <m>g</m> be an increasing on the closed interval <m>[a,b]</m>, and let <m>f</m> be a continuous function on <m>[a,b]</m>, and let <m>f</m> be a continuous function on <m>[a,b]</m>. Let <m>P = \{x_0,\ldots,x_n\}</m> be a partition of <m>[a,b]</m> with</p>
<md> a = x_0 &lt;x_1 &lt; \ldots&lt; x_n =b.</md>
<p>We define the lower Darboux-Stieltjes sum by</p>
<md> L(f,g,P) = \sum_{k=1}^n \inf_{x\in[x_{k-1},x_k]}f(x)(g(x_k)-g(x_{k-1})),</md>
<p>and the upper Darboux-Stieltjes sum by</p>
<md> U(f,g,P) = \sum_{k=1}^n \sup_{x\in[x_{k-1},x_k]}f(x)(g(x_k)-g(x_{k-1})).</md>
<p>The <em>Riemann-Stieltjes integral of <m>f</m> with respect to <m>g</m></em>,<idx><h>Riemann-Stieltjes integral</h></idx> <m>\int_a^b f\,dg</m>, is defined as</p>
<md> \int_a^b f\,dg = \sup_P L(f,g,P) = \inf_P U(f,g,P). </md>
<p>Note that, if <m>g(x)= x</m>, then the Riemann-Stieltjes integral is the same as the Riemann integral. For arbitrary increasing <m>g</m>, the theory of Riemann-Stieltjes integrals aligns closely with that of Riemann integrals.</p>
<p>More generally, if <m>g</m> is a function of bounded variation, we can define the Riemann-Stieltjes integral <m>\int_a^b f\,dg</m>, either by considering sums of the form</p>
<md> \sum_{k=1}^n f(x_k^*)(g(x_k)-g(x_{k-1})),</md>
<p>for partitions <m>\{x_0,\ldots,x_n\}</m> of <m>[a,b]</m>, and <m>x_k^* \in [x_{k-1},x_k]</m>; or by defining</p>
<md> \int_a^b f\,dg = \int_a^b f\,dg_+ - \int_a^b f\,dg_-,</md>
<p>where <m>g= g_+ - g_-</m> is the Jordan decomposition of <m>g</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>\varphi</m> be a linear functional on <m>C([a,b])</m>. Riesz constructs a function of bounded variation <m>g</m> using <m>\varphi</m>. One way to do this, as done in <xref ref="RieszNagyFA"/>, is to extend the domain of <m>\varphi</m> to contain bounded point-wise limits of increasing continuous functions. The function <m>g</m> is then defined by</p>
<md> g(x) = \varphi(\chi_{[0,x]}).</md>
<p>It is then shown that that</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_a^b f\,dg,</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in C([a,b])</m>.</p>
<p>One can show that the function <m>g</m> is right-continuous. Thus, by Theorem <xref ref="thm-signed-meas-1-1-bv"/>, there is a Borel signed measure <m>\nu</m> on <m>[a,b]</m> such that <m>\nu([a,x]) = f(x)</m> for all <m>x \in [a,b]</m>. It can be shown that, if <m>f</m> is a continuous function on <m>[a,b]</m> then</p>
<md> \int_a^bf\,dg = \int_{[a,b]} f\,d\nu.</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md> \varphi(f) = \int_{[a,b]} f\,d\nu,</md>
<p>and we recover the measure theoretic description of the dual of <m>C([a,b])</m>.</p>
</subsection>
</section>
<exercises>
<exercise xml:id="exer-operator-norm">
<p>Prove Proposition <xref ref="prop-operator-norm"/>.
    That is, show that the operator norm <m>\|\cdot\|_\mathrm{op}</m> is a norm on the dual space <m>V^*</m>, where <m>V</m> is a normed vector space.</p>
<p>Further show that</p>
<md> \|\varphi\|_{\mathrm{op}} = \inf \{M  \colon |\varphi(v)|\leq M\|v\| \text{ for all }v \in V\}</md>
<p>for all <m>\varphi \in V^*.</m></p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-riesz-rep-p-1">
<p>Prove Theorem <xref ref="thm-riesz-rep-Lp"/> for the case <m>p = 1</m>.
    That is, assuming that <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure space, show that if <m>\varphi \in (L^1(X,\mu))^*</m> that there is a <m>g \in L^\infty(X,\mu)</m> with <m>\|g\|_\infty = \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}</m> such that</p>
<md>\varphi(f) = \int_X fg \,d\mu</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in L^1(X,\mu)</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-yes-dual">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set, and let <m>c</m> be the counting measure on the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>P(X)</m> of all subsets of <m>X</m>.
	We will show that <m>(\ell^1(X))^* \simeq \ell^\infty(X)</m> by the same isomorphism used in Theorem <xref ref="thm-riesz-rep-Lp"/>.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>For each <m>f \in \ell^1(X)</m>, let <m>L_f = \{x \in X \colon f(x) \neq 0\}</m>. Show that <m>L_f</m> is a countable set, and that 
		<md> \int_X f\,dc = \sum_{x \in L_f} f(x). </md>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take <m>g \in \ell^\infty(X)</m>. Define 
		<md> T_g(f) = \int_X gf\,dc</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in \ell^1(X)</m>. Show that <m>T_g</m> is a linear functional on <m>\ell^1(X)</m> with <m>\|T_g\|_\mathrm{op}= \|g\|_\infty</m>. (You should be able to prove this directly without reference to the proof of Lemma <xref ref="lem-holder-for-dual-p-1"/>).</p>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take <m>\varphi\in (\ell^1(X))^*</m>. For each <m>x \in X</m>, let <m>e_x</m> be the function
		<md> e_x(y) = \begin{cases} 1 &amp;\text{if }y=x\\
		0 &amp; \text{if }y\neq x.\end{cases} </md>
<p>Show that <m>e_x \in \ell^1(X)</m> with <m>\|e_x\|_1 = 1</m>, for all <m>x\in X</m>.</p>
<p>Define a function <m>g</m> on <m>X</m> by <m>g(x) = \varphi(e_x)</m>. Show that <m>g\in \ell^\infty(X)</m>. Show that <m>\varphi = T_g</m>.</p>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-not-dual">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be an uncountable set, and let <m>c</m> be the counting measure on the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>P(X)</m> of all subsets of <m>X</m>.
	Let <m>c_0</m> be the restriction of <m>c</m> to the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>\mathcal{M}</m> of all subsets of <m>X</m> which are either countable or cocountable (see Exercise <xref ref="exer-cocount-measure"/> for more on <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.)
	We will show that <m>(L^1(X,c_0))^*</m> is not <m>L^\infty(X,c_0)</m>.
	Exercise <xref ref="exer-yes-dual"/> should be completed before this exercise.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that <m>L^1(X,c_0)= \ell^1(X)</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that a simple function <m>\varphi</m> on <m>(X,\mathcal{M},c_0)</m> must be constant on a cocountable set. Conclude that <m>L^\infty(X,c_0) \subsetneq \ell^\infty(X)</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that the map <m>g \mapsto T_g</m> is not an isomorphism from <m>L^\infty(X,c_0)</m> to <m>(L^1(X,c_0))^*)</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-c0">
<p><idx><h sortby="c0">{<m>c_0</m>}</h></idx>
Denote by <m>c_0</m> all sequences of real numbers which converges to <m>0</m>; and
for each <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>.
Note that <m>c_0 \subseteq \ell^\infty</m>.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that <m>c_0</m> is a Banach space with the <m>\infty</m>-norm.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that the collection of sequences which are <m>0</m> for all but finitely many terms are dense in <m>c_0</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that <m>c_0</m> is separable.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-dual-of-c0">
<p><idx><h sortby="c0">{<m>c_0</m>}</h><h>dual of <m>c_0</m></h></idx>
Denote by <m>c_0</m> all sequences of real numbers which converges to <m>0</m>; and
for each <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>, denote by <m>e_n</m> the  sequence which is <m>1</m> in the <m>n</m>th position, and <m>0</m> in all other positions.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Take <m>a = (a_n)_n \in \ell^1</m>.
Show that the map
<md>
\begin{aligned}
T_a \colon &amp; c_0 \rightarrow \mathbb{R} \\
&amp; (b_n)_n \mapsto \sum_{n=1}^\infty a_nb_n
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>defines a linear functional on <m>c_0</m>, with <m>\|T_a\|_\mathrm{op} = \|a\|_1</m>.</p>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take <m>\varphi \in (c_0)^*</m>. For each <m>n</m>, let <m>a_n = \varphi(e_n)</m>.
Show that <m>(a_n)_n \in \ell^1</m> and that <m>\varphi = T_a</m>. (HINT: consider <m>\varphi(\sum_{n=1}^N \gamma_n e_n)</m> where <m>\gamma_n = \operatorname{sgn}(\varphi(e_n))</m>).</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that the map <m>T \colon a \mapsto T_a</m> is an isometric linear bijection from <m>\ell^1</m> to <m>(c_0)^*</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-dual-of-linf">
<ol>
<li><p>Show that, if <m>a = (a_n)_n \in \ell^1</m>, then the map <m>T_a</m> defined by
	<md> T_a((b_n)_n) = \sum_{n=1}^\infty a_n b_n</md>
<p>for all <m>(b_n)_n \in \ell^\infty</m> is a linear functional on <m>\ell^\infty</m>.</p>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take any <m>\varphi \in (\ell^\infty)^*</m>. For each <m>n</m>, let <m>a_n =  \varphi(e_n)</m>, where <m>e_n</m> is defined as in Exercise <xref ref="exer-dual-of-c0"/>.
	Show that <m>a=(a_n)_n \in \ell^1</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take <m>\varphi \in (\ell^\infty)^*</m> and let <m>a=(a_n)_n</m> be as in part (ii). Show that <m>\varphi(b) = T_a(b)</m> for all <m>b \in c_0</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that if <m>\varphi \in (\ell^\infty)^*</m>, then there is an <m>a \in \ell^1</m> and a <m>\psi \in (\ell^\infty)^*</m> with <m>\psi|_{c_0}=0</m> such that
	<md> \varphi = T_a + \psi. </md>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-norm-on-bfa">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> be a measurable space. A <em>finitely additive signed measure</em><idx><h>signed measure</h><h>finitely additive</h></idx> on <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> is a function <m>\nu \colon \mathcal{M}\rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> such that</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\nu(\emptyset)=0</m>; and</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>\nu\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k\right) = \sum_{k=1}^n \nu(E_k)</m> when <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^n</m> are disjoint sets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>A finitely additive signed measure is <em>bounded</em><idx><h>signed measure</h><h>bounded finitely additive</h></idx> if</p>
<md> |\nu|(X) := \sup\left\{\sum_{k=1}^n \nu(E_k) \colon \{E_k\}_{k=1}^n\subseteq\mathcal{M} \text{ disjoint sets.}\}\right\}&lt;\infty.</md>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that the collection of all bounded finitely additive signed measures on <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> forms a vector space.</p>
</li>
<li><p>If <m>\nu</m> is a bounded finitely additive signed measure, let <m>\|\nu\|_\mathrm{var} = |\nu|(X)</m>. Show that <m>\|\cdot\|_\mathrm{var}</m> is a norm on the vector space of bounded finitely additive signed measures on <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-bfa-integral">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> be a measurable space and let <m>\nu</m> be a bounded finitely additive signed measure on <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m>.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Let <m>\varphi = \sum_{k=1}^n c_k \chi_{E_k}</m> be a simple function, where <m>c_1,\ldots,c_n</m> are distinct, and <m>E_1,\ldots,E_n</m> are disjoint.
		Define <m>\int_X \varphi \,d\mu</m> by
		<md> \int_X \varphi\,d\nu = \sum_{k=1}^n c_k \nu(E_k). </md>
<p>Show that</p>
<md> \left| \int_X \varphi\,d\nu\right| \leq \|\nu\|_{\mathrm{var}} \|\varphi\|_\infty.</md>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>Let <m>f</m> be a bounded, measurable function on <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m>.
		Let <m>(\phi_n)_n</m> be a sequence of simple functions with <m>\phi_n \leq f</m> for all <m>n</m>, which converge uniformly to <m>f</m> (Such a sequence exists by Exercise <xref ref="exer-uniform-convergence"/>).
		Define <m>\int_X f\,d\nu</m> by
		<md>\int_X f\,d\nu = \lim_{n\rightarrow \infty} \int_X \varphi\,d\nu.</md>
<p>Show that <m>\int_X f\,d\nu</m> is independent on the choice of sequence <m>(\phi_n)_n</m>.</p>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-kantor">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space and let <m>\mathsf{BFA}(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be the normed vector space of all bounded finitely additive signed measures on <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> which are absolutely continuous with respect to <m>\mu</m>.
	That is, <m>\mathsf{BFA}(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is the collection of all bounded finitely additive signed measures <m>\nu</m> such that <m>\nu(E) = 0</m> whenever <m>\mu(E)=0</m>.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that 
		<md> \left| \int_X f\,d\nu \right| \leq \|\nu\|_\mathrm{var} \|f\|_\infty</md>
<p>for all <m>f \in L^\infty(X,\mu)</m> and <m>\nu \in \mathsf{BFA}(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m>.</p>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>For <m>\nu \in \mathsf{BFA}(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m>, define <m>T_\nu \colon L^\infty(X,\mu) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> by
		<md> T_\nu(f) = \int_X f\,d\nu. </md>
<p>Show that <m>T_\nu</m> is a bounded linear functional on <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m> such that <m>\|T_\nu\|_\mathrm{op} = \|\nu\|_\mathrm{var}.</m></p>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>Let <m>\varphi</m> be a bounded linear functional on <m>L^\infty(X,\mu)</m>.
		Define <m>\nu</m> by <m>\nu(E) = \varphi(\chi_E)</m> for all <m>E \in \mathcal{M}</m>.
		Show that <m>\nu \in \mathsf{BFA}(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and that <m>\|\nu\|_\mathrm{var} = \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op}.</m></p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that the map <m>T \colon \mathsf{BFA}(X,\mathcal{M},\mu) \rightarrow (L^\infty(X,\mu))^*</m> defined by <m>T(\nu) = T_\nu</m> is a bijective linear map with <m>\|T(\nu)\|_\mathrm{op}= \|\nu\|_\mathrm{var}.</m>
		That is, conclude <m>\mathsf{BFA}(X,\mathcal{M},\mu) \simeq (L^\infty(X,\mu))^*.</m></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>The above result is known as the Kantorovitch Representation Theorem.<idx><h>Kantorovitch Representation Theorem</h></idx></p>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<p>Prove Proposition <xref ref="prop-compact-finite-intersection"/>.
	That is, show that <m>X</m> is compact, if and only if whenever <m>\{F_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m> is a collection of closed sets satisfying <m>\bigcap_{k=1}^nF_k \neq \emptyset</m> for any <m>F_1,\ldots,F_n \in \{F_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m>, then</p>
<md> \bigcap_{\alpha\in A}F_\alpha \neq \emptyset.</md>
<p>(HINT: Note that <m>\bigcap_{\alpha\in A}F_\alpha \neq \emptyset = \emptyset</m> if and only if <m>\{X \backslash F_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A}</m> is an open cover of <m>X</m>.)</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-Borel-on-R-Radon">
<p>Let <m>\mu</m> be a Borel measure on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
	Show that <m>\mu</m> is inner regular on all open subsets <m>U \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
	(HINT: consider the three cases, (i) <m>\mu(U) = \infty</m>; (ii) <m>\mu(U)&lt;\infty</m> and <m>U</m> is a disjoint union of finitely many open intervals; and (iii) <m>\mu(U)&lt;\infty</m> and <m>U</m> is a disjoint union of infinitely many open intervals.)</p>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space. Show that <m>C_c(X)</m> is dense in <m>C_0(X)</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-norm-of-positive">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space <m>X</m> and let <m>\varphi</m> be a positive linear functional on <m>C_0(X)</m>.
	Show that</p>
<md> \|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \sup\{\varphi(f) \colon \|f\|_\infty =1,\ f \geq 0\}.</md>
<p>If <m>X</m> is compact and <m>\varphi</m> is a positive linear functional on <m>C(X)</m>, show that <m>\|\varphi\|_\mathrm{op} = \varphi(1)</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-radon-vec-space">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact Hausdorff space and let <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m> be all finite Radon signed measures on <m>X</m>.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m> is a vector space under the operations
		<md>
\begin{aligned}
(\nu + \mu)(E)&amp;= \nu(E) + \mu(E)\text{ and}\\
			(c\mu)(E) &amp;= c \mu(E),
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>for <m>\mu,\nu \in \mathcal{M}(X)</m> and <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that <m>\|\cdot\|_\mathrm{var}</m> defines a norm on <m>\mathcal{M}(X)</m>, where
		<md> \|\nu\|_\mathrm{var} = |\nu|(X) </md>
<p>for all <m>\nu \in \mathcal{M}(X)</m>. (Recall, that <m>|\nu|(X)</m> is the total variation of <m>\nu</m>.)</p>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
</exercises>
</chapter>
